node.text: Now here’s an absolute monster of a wave from @afonsobandagarra that is oh so worthy of recognition. Speaking of which, @nicvonrupp and his company @thebrusco have launched their #bruscochargerofthemonth comp, awarding the winner with a pack of surf goodies. “Our whole idea was to give credit and recognition to those underground chargers that constantly search for the best and heaviest waves in the Atlantic Ocean,” said Nic. “We want to inspire people to push their limits and there is no better example than these guys that put their lives on the line only for the pure love of surfing. This inspires me everyday and I believe it will also inspire the younger generations.” We couldn’t have said it better. Head over to the site for a full run down of this session and some insight from Afonso. Vid @vanlife_productions

node.text: Time for a 2-5 minute edit? Think most of us have these days. Every Friday, we'll be dropping one of our exclusive edits striaght to IG. First up, this session from deepest Cornwall in February of last year. The day before, the south west had been dripped by a blizzard, freezing over the roads and making travel damn near impossible. But a lucky crew managed to make the journey, hinderance free, and were greeted by a few barrels off this reefbreak. Featuring @alan_stokes @skindoggydog and many more, all shot by @biskit_bodyboarding you can find the full feature on the site, just search Cornwall in our shiny new nav bar.

node.text: @paigealms: “Pe’ahi is where I learned to surf big waves, and I am fortunate to have grown up in Haiku and have this wave right in my backyard. It is by far the heaviest big wave that I have ever surfed, and the most technical when it comes to manoeuvrability and the lines you can draw. As far as the success that the wave has brought me, there has been a lot of love, respect, and constantly humbling by the power of the ocean. I think maybe the wave knows how much I appreciate it, and wants to share the love. That and years of hard work, training, preparation, perseverance, and trusting in the path that I believe has already been paved for me—what some people call fate.” Hit the link in bio for the full  interview. Pics @wsl

node.text: “With swell on the way and the wind forecast swirling, the three of us boarded a flight, together with a bunch of boards, a handful of cameras, and more than a few doubts. But we were flying into uncharted territory, so even if we didn’t score, that still had to count for something. I guess we could have gone somewhere guaranteed—chased a swell to a sure thing that took a lot less work and a lot less time. But sometimes the experience of searching is just as important as what you find.” Hit the link in bio for full on journey into unchartered territory. Pics @beitzmedia

node.text: Luke Saranah (@l_r_s_) is a tugboat decky and roof plumber from Western Australia. He’s also a superb and fearless barrel hunter who’d be at home in the sketchiest of lineups. Luke competed a bit as a grommet before evolving into a committed traveler, spending his available time hunting heaving pits. “I met him on a trip a few years ago at Desert Point, saw him get one wave and thought who the hell is this,” says lensman @driftwoodphotography_mr, “since then I have been working with him closely.” Hit the link in bio for the full interview.

node.text: This is it. The full wrap from Ireland, England and Scotland as Hurricane Larry sent an incredible pulse of swell across the Atlantic. Like we’ve said before, it’s incredibly rare that swell from an actual hurricane travels 2,000 miles across the ocean and reaches the likes of the UK and Ireland. How it all panned out, link in bio. Pic 1) Scotland from Zurf Collection pic 2) Ireland and @taz_knight by @garymccallphoto 3) @gearoidmcdaid on his 1,000,000th barrel of the day from Tuesday from @conor_flanagan_photography and 4) England got some too by @_rtshots
